Home

Your computer is your universe.

Timeway is a whimsical, dream-like explorer application that transforms your computer files into a universe.

Run free and bounce around in beautiful, retro pixel worlds that represent your filesystem- directories are your "realms", and these realms can be traversed using portals, just as you would traverse your file system by navigating folders.




Customise realms, manage files, and shape your universe.

Pick up files and portals and move between realms- this moves your actual files on your computer.
Customise realms with custom skies, grass, trees, and background music. You can even customise the terrain with the terraformer tool.

Not in the mood to create assets? No problem. Timeway provides over 150 beautiful realm templates to choose from- simply create a new folder portal and select from one of the many templates available.




Not just an explorer.

Timeway features an editor similar to Microsoft's Onenote; you can create notes, paste images, and take photos with your camera. Timeway is also your productivity platform.




Starts up within 3 seconds. Loads files without lag. Smooth constant framerate. All while running on low-power processors.

Timeway is built on top of the Processing framework using a custom engine, which is specifically optimised to run with minimal lag, and to render graphics on low-power graphics chips, thus enabling you to use it as a general-purpose application on laptops, without consuming much power or resources.




Download Timeway


Include templates









Templates are not necessary for Timeway to run, but if you don't include them, you won't be able to choose from 150 premade realms.

Please note the Android version is very experimental. Once you download the app, you will need to enable special permissions to access all files.

Your download has started!

Your download should be complete in a few minutes.

Once complete, extract the files from the zip folder and run "Timeway.exe" on Windows, or right-click and click "Run as application" for Linux.

If you're using Android, installation involves more steps due to the experimental nature of the Android port. Refer to this section on the GitHub release page for more information.
